ch 4 summary:
1. Context of Evolution & Compatibility
ď‚· The Reality: Applications change inevitably (new fields, schema updates).
ď‚· Rolling Upgrades (Staged Rollout): Deploying a new version to a few nodes at a time
without downtime. This means old and new versions of code/data co-exist
simultaneously.
ď‚· Compatibility Types:
o Backward Compatibility: Newer code can read data written by older code (Easy
to achieve).
o Forward Compatibility: Older code can read data written by newer code
(Tricker; requires ignoring unknown additions).
2. Two Data Representations
1. In-Memory: Objects, structs, lists, pointers optimized for CPU access.
2. On-Disk / Network: Self-contained sequence of bytes (Pointers make no sense here).
ď‚· Definitions:
o Encoding (Serialization/Marshalling): In-memory structure $\rightarrow$ Byte
sequence.
o Decoding (Deserialization/Unmarshalling): Byte sequence $\rightarrow$ In-
memory structure.
3. Language-Specific Formats (e.g., Java Serializable, Python pickle)
ď‚· Pros: Convenient for quick, transient setups.
ď‚· Cons (Exam Pitfalls):
o Tied to one specific programming language.
o Security Vulnerability: Decoding can instantiate arbitrary classes, leading to
Remote Code Execution (RCE).
o Versioning, compatibility, and efficiency (CPU/size) are usually bad
afterthoughts.
4. Textual Formats (JSON, XML, CSV)
ď‚· Pros: Widespread, human-readable, excellent web browser/interchange support.
ď‚· Cons:
o Number Ambiguity: JSON doesn't distinguish integers from floats and loses
precision for numbers $> 2^{53}$ (Twitter API passes tweet IDs as strings to fix
this).
o No Binary String Support: Raw bytes must be encoded into text using Base64,
which hacks the structure and increases data size by 33%.
o Optional schemas (XML Schema / JSON Schema) are complicated; CSV has no
schema at all (vague escaping rules).
5. Binary Encodings without Schemas (e.g., MessagePack, BSON)
ď‚· Concept: Extends datatypes (distinguishes floats/integers) but retains JSON/XML data
models.
ď‚· The Catch: Since they are schemaless, they must include all field names as text
strings inside the encoded data (e.g., storing the actual string "userName"). This limits
space savings.
6. Binary Encodings with Schemas (Thrift & Protocol Buffers)
ď‚· Concept: Require an Interface Definition Language (IDL) schema and code generation
tools for compile-time type checking.
ď‚· Mechanics: They omit field names entirely from the byte stream. Instead, they use Field
Tags (numbers like 1, 2, 3 mapped in the schema) as compact aliases.
ď‚· Thrift Formats: Has BinaryProtocol and CompactProtocol (the latter uses variable-
length integers and bit packing to save space).
ď‚· Schema Evolution Rules:
o Forward compatibility: Old code ignores unrecognized field tags via datatype
size metadata annotations.
o Backward compatibility: New fields added must be optional or have default
values (never required), so reading old data doesn't trigger runtime failures.
o Removed fields must be optional; their tags can never be reused.
7. Apache Avro
ď‚· Concept: Started for Hadoop. Uses a schema but completely lacks tag numbers. It is
the most compact binary encoding (just values concatenated together).
ď‚· The Mechanism: * Writerâ€™s Schema: The schema version the encoding process used.
o Readerâ€™s Schema: The schema version the decoding process expects.
o Resolution: The Avro library looks at both schemas side-by-side and translates
fields by matching their literal names.
ď‚· Evolution Rules: You can only add/remove a field that has a default value. To allow
null, you must explicitly use a Union Type (union { null, long }), preventing
unexpected null pointer bugs.
ď‚· How Reader finds Writer's Schema:
1. Large Files (Hadoop): Include the schema once at the beginning of the file
container.
2. Databases: Include a tiny schema version number at the start of each record.
3. Network (RPC): Negotiate the schema version upon connection setup.
ď‚· Dynamic Generation: Highly friendly to relational database dumps. Column names
automatically map to Avro field names without needing hand-assigned tags. Works
perfectly with dynamic languages (Pig/Python) without requiring explicit code
generation.
8. Summary of Schema Merits
ď‚· Compact (omits field names).
ď‚· Acts as up-to-date documentation.
ď‚· Allows static type checking via code generation.
ď‚· Enables verification of backward/forward compatibility before deployment.
9. Modes of Dataflow
A. Dataflow Through Databases
ď‚· Concept: Writing data is sending a message to your future self.
ď‚· Snag: Forward compatibility is critical because older code might read a row modified by
newer code. If the older code updates and re-saves the row, it must preserve unknown
fields to avoid data loss.
ď‚· Principle: Data outlives code (5-year-old records exist in historical schemas while code
upgrades in minutes).
B. Dataflow Through Services (REST and RPC)
ď‚· Web Services: Client/Server communication over HTTP. Includes REST (Design
philosophy leveraging HTTP features, simple data formats like JSON) and SOAP (XML-
based contract using WSDL, highly complex, depends on heavy IDE tooling).
ď‚· The Flaws of RPC (Remote Procedure Call): Tries to make remote network requests
look like local function calls (Location Transparency). This abstraction is
fundamentally flawed because:
o Network requests are unpredictable (drops, slowness) and can timeout without a
result.
o Retrying failed requests can duplicate execution unless Idempotence is
implemented.
o Latency is wildly variable.
o Large objects or complex pointers cannot be passed efficiently.
o Translating types across different languages can cause precision loss.
ď‚· Modern RPC (gRPC, Finagle): Explicitly handles network realities using
futures/promises for async failures and streams for continuous data exchange. REST is
preferred for public APIs; RPC is used for internal, single-datacenter service
communication.
C. Message-Passing Dataflow (Asynchronous)
ď‚· Message Brokers (e.g., Kafka, RabbitMQ): Senders publish to named queues/topics
asynchronously via a broker instead of direct connections.
ď‚· Broker Advantages: Acts as a buffer, automatically redelivers crashed messages,
decouples sender from recipient IP, and allows fan-out to multiple consumers.
ď‚· Distributed Actor Frameworks (e.g., Akka, Orleans, Erlang OTP): Scales
concurrency across multiple nodes using asynchronous message passing. Inherently
expects message drops, making location transparency work better than in classic RPC.
Rolling upgrades still require explicit Avro/Protobuf compatibility tuning over default
language serialization.
10. Core Summary Checklist for the Exam
ď‚· Language Encodings: Bad for long-term/cross-language use; security risk (RCE).
ď‚· Protobuf/Thrift: Use numerical Field Tags.
ď‚· Avro: Uses Writer/Reader schema resolution by field name; no tags.
ď‚· OLTP vs. OLAP data formats: Databases require forward/backward compatibility;
archival storage uses immutable column formats (Parquet) via Avro containers.
ď‚· RPC Flaw Keyword: Location Transparency is a flawed illusion